  Authored by OpenAgreements contributors. District of Columbia-specific
  analysis informed by the quote-verified District of Columbia practice note.
  Licensed under CC BY 4.0.
layout_id: cover-standard-signature-v1
style_id: openagreements-default-v1
document:
  title: Employee Restrictive Covenant Agreement
  label: OpenAgreements Employee Restrictive Covenant (District of Columbia)
  version: 0.1.0
  license: Free to use under CC BY 4.0
  include_cloud_doc_line: true
  defined_term_highlight_mode: definition_site_only
  cover_row_height: 317
sections:
  cover_terms:
    section_label: Cover Terms
    heading_title: Cover Terms
  standard_terms:
    section_label: Standard Terms
    heading_title: Standard Terms
  signature:
    section_label: Signature Page
    heading_title: Signatures
fields:
  - name: employer_name
    type: string
    description: Legal name of the employer
    display_label: Employer
    section: Parties
  - name: employer_signatory_name
    type: string
    description: Full name of the authorized signatory signing for the employer
    display_label: Employer Signatory Name
    section: Parties
  - name: employer_signatory_title
    type: string
    description: Title of the authorized signatory signing for the employer
    display_label: Employer Signatory Title
    section: Parties
  - name: employee_name
    type: string
    description: Full legal name of the employee
    display_label: Employee
    section: Parties
  - name: employee_title
    type: string
    description: Employee job title or position (optional)
    display_label: Employee Title / Position
    default: ''
    section: Parties
  - name: effective_date
    type: date
    description: >-
      Effective date of this agreement — the date the last party signs. It
      anchors the durations stated in Cover Terms.
    display_label: Effective Date
    section: Timing
  - name: notice_date
    type: date
    description: >-
      Date the employer delivered the non-compete provision to the employee in
      writing. For a valid highly compensated employee non-compete the employer
      must provide it at least 14 days before the individual commences
      employment, or, for a current employee, at least 14 days before the
      employee must execute the agreement.
    display_label: Advance Delivery Date
    section: Timing
    rationale_source: legislation
    requirement_id: REQ-labor-and-employment-law.restrictive-covenant-agreement.district-of-columbia.deliver-the-covenant-in-writing-fourteen-days-in-advance
  - name: governing_law
    type: string
    description: >-
      Governing law jurisdiction. Coverage under the District's ban keys to
      where the employee works — more than 50% of work time in the District, or
      a District-based role with substantial District work — not to the law
      named in the clause, so this should remain the District of Columbia for a
      District-based worker.
    display_label: Governing Law
    section: Legal
    default: District of Columbia
    rationale_source: editorial
  - name: minimum_qualifying_compensation
    type: string
    description: >-
      Minimum qualifying annual compensation the worker must earn to be a highly
      compensated employee who may be bound by a non-compete. The statutory base
      is $150,000, adjusted upward each year for inflation; the Department of
      Employment Services publishes the current figure. The default is the 2026
      figure; replace it with the figure for the year the covenant is proposed.
    display_label: Minimum Qualifying Annual Compensation
    default: $162,164
    section: District of Columbia Statutory Gates
    default_value_rationale: >-
      $162,164 is the 2026 minimum qualifying annual compensation published in
      the D.C. Department of Employment Services Public Notice on the Prohibition
      on Non-Compete Clauses (Jan. 1, 2026). The statute indexes this figure to
      inflation each year, so counsel should confirm the published figure for
      the year the covenant is proposed rather than relying on the $150,000
      statutory base.
    rationale_source: regulation
    requirement_id: REQ-labor-and-employment-law.restrictive-covenant-agreement.district-of-columbia.gate-non-compete-by-minimum-qualifying-compensation
  - name: medical_specialist_threshold
    type: string
    description: >-
      Minimum qualifying annual compensation for a medical specialist. The
      statutory base is $250,000, adjusted upward each year for inflation; the
      Department of Employment Services publishes the current figure. The
      default is the 2026 figure; replace it with the figure for the year the
      covenant is proposed.
    display_label: Medical Specialist Minimum Compensation
    default: $270,274
    section: District of Columbia Statutory Gates
    default_value_rationale: >-
      $270,274 is the 2026 medical specialist threshold published in the D.C.
      Department of Employment Services Public Notice on the Prohibition on
      Non-Compete Clauses (Jan. 1, 2026), tracking the $250,000 statutory base
      as adjusted for inflation.
    rationale_source: regulation
    requirement_id: REQ-labor-and-employment-law.restrictive-covenant-agreement.district-of-columbia.gate-non-compete-by-minimum-qualifying-compensation
  - name: confidentiality_trade_secret_duration
    type: string
    description: Duration of confidentiality obligations for trade secrets
    display_label: Trade Secrets Duration
    default: Perpetual
    section: Confidentiality
  - name: confidentiality_other_duration
    type: string
    description: Duration of confidentiality obligations for non-trade-secret information
    display_label: Other Confidential Information Duration
    default: 24 months
    section: Confidentiality
    default_value_rationale: >-
      24 months is common for non-trade-secret confidentiality obligations in
      employment agreements. A finite term keeps the non-secret obligation from
      functioning as a bar on competitive employment, which would risk
      recharacterization as a banned non-compete provision.
    rationale_source: editorial
  - name: employee_nonsolicit_included
    type: boolean
    description: Whether the employee non-solicitation covenant is included
    display_label: Employee Non-Solicitation Included
    default: true
    section: Employee Non-Solicitation
  - name: employee_nonsolicit_duration
    type: string
    description: Duration of employee non-solicitation restriction
    display_label: Employee Non-Solicitation Duration
    default: 24 months
    section: Employee Non-Solicitation
    default_value_rationale: >-
      24 months matches the modal employee non-solicit term observed in benchmarked, publicly-filed
      employee agreements; 12 months is the common lighter alternative. The District's ban does not
      speak to employee non-solicits, so the clause is judged under common-law reasonableness; a
      shorter term supports treating it as a limited restraint on active solicitation.
    rationale_source: editorial
  - name: covered_employee_period
    type: string
    description: >-
      Lookback period for determining which employees are covered by the
      non-solicitation restriction.
    display_label: Covered Employee Period
    default: 12 months
    section: Employee Non-Solicitation
    default_value_rationale: >-
      12 months is the most common lookback period for employee non-solicitation
      scope.
  - name: customer_nonsolicit_included
    type: boolean
    description: Whether the customer/partner non-solicitation covenant is included
    display_label: Customer Non-Solicitation Included
    default: true
    section: Customer Non-Solicitation
  - name: customer_nonsolicit_duration
    type: string
    description: Duration of customer/partner non-solicitation restriction
    display_label: Customer Non-Solicitation Duration
    default: 12 months
    section: Customer Non-Solicitation
    default_value_rationale: >-
      12 months is a common enforceable duration. A District customer
      non-solicit sits outside the statutory ban but is still a restraint of
      trade judged for reasonableness under common law (Ellis), and a shorter
      term supports that characterization.
  - name: covered_customer_period
    type: string
    description: >-
      Lookback period for determining which customers are covered by the
      non-solicitation restriction.
    display_label: Covered Customer Period
    default: 12 months
    section: Customer Non-Solicitation
    default_value_rationale: >-
      12 months is the most common lookback period for customer non-solicitation
      scope.
  - name: noncompete_included
    type: boolean
    description: >-
      Whether the non-competition covenant is included. Beginning October 1,
      2022 an employer may not require or request that a covered employee — a
      District-based worker below the minimum qualifying annual compensation —
      sign or comply with a non-compete provision, and such a provision entered
      into on or after that date is void as a matter of law. A non-compete
      survives only against a highly compensated employee and only if it clears
      every statutory validity gate: a stated functional scope and geographic
      limits, a term of no more than 365 calendar days from separation (730 for
      a medical specialist), and 14-day advance written delivery. This template
      recites those gates when the covenant is included.
    display_label: Non-Competition Included
    default: false
    section: Non-Competition
    default_value_rationale: >-
      Conservative default. For a covered employee a District non-compete is
      banned and void, and subjecting an employee to one carries monetary relief
      of $500–$1,000 per employee, at least $1,500 for an attempt to enforce a
      void covenant, and at least $3,000 for a subsequent violation, plus
      administrative penalties and Attorney General enforcement. Include only
      after confirming the worker is a highly compensated employee at or above
      the published threshold, the covenant states its functional scope and
      geography, its term stays within the calendar-day cap, and the covenant
      was delivered in writing at least 14 days in advance with the prescribed
      statutory notice.
    rationale_source: legislation
    requirement_id: REQ-labor-and-employment-law.restrictive-covenant-agreement.district-of-columbia.exclude-non-competes-for-covered-employees
  - name: noncompete_duration
    type: string
    description: >-
      Duration of the non-competition restriction, measured in calendar days
      from separation. It must not exceed 365 calendar days from the date the
      employee separates, or 730 calendar days for a medical specialist.
    display_label: Non-Competition Duration
    default: 365 calendar days
    section: Non-Competition
    default_value_rationale: >-
      365 calendar days is the statutory ceiling for a non-medical highly
      compensated employee measured from separation. A term stated in years
      risks silently overshooting the day count, so the default is expressed in
      calendar days; a medical specialist may run to 730 calendar days.
    rationale_source: legislation
    requirement_id: REQ-labor-and-employment-law.restrictive-covenant-agreement.district-of-columbia.cap-the-term-at-365-or-730-calendar-days
  - name: territory
    type: string
    description: >-
      Geographic scope of the non-competition restriction. Section
      32-581.03(a)(1)(B) makes stated geographical limitations a condition of a
      valid highly compensated employee non-compete, so this must be an explicit,
      bounded territory matched to where the employee works.
    display_label: Restricted Territory
    default: the geographic area in which the Employee performed work for Employer
    section: Non-Competition
    default_value_rationale: >-
      Tied to where the employee actually performed work rather than the
      employer's entire footprint. Section 32-581.03(a)(1)(B) requires the
      covenant to specify its geographical limitations, and a covenant silent on
      geography is not valid and enforceable even for a worker far above the pay
      threshold.
  - name: competitive_business_definition
    type: string
    description: >-
      Description of the services, roles, industry, or competing entities the
      employee is restricted from performing work in or on behalf of. Section
      32-581.03(a)(1)(A) makes a stated functional scope a condition of a valid
      highly compensated employee non-compete.
    display_label: Competitive Business
    section: Non-Competition
  - name: specified_competitors
    type: string
    description: >-
      Optional named list of specific competing entities. Naming the employer's
      real competitors is the most concrete way to satisfy the competing-entities
      limb of the functional-scope requirement and shrinks the scope a reviewer
      must defend.
    display_label: Specified Competitors
    default: ''
    section: Non-Competition
    rationale_source: legislation
    requirement_id: REQ-labor-and-employment-law.restrictive-covenant-agreement.district-of-columbia.specify-functional-scope-and-geographic-limits
  - name: nondisparagement_duration
    type: string
    description: Duration of non-disparagement obligation (measured from termination)
    display_label: Non-Disparagement Duration
    default: 24 months
    section: Non-Disparagement
    default_value_rationale: 24 months is common for employment non-disparagement provisions.
priority_fields:
  - employer_name
  - employee_name
